sadvantages are that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>it can be a demanding, expensive and time-consuming process</li>\n  <li>you’ll own a smaller share of your business (although your share could eventually be worth more money if your business succeeds)</li>\n  <li>you might lose the power to make certain management decisions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>More information</h2>\n\n<p>Get detailed guidance on <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.bvca.co.uk/PEVCExplained/features/WhatisPE\" title=\":BVCA: shares and other investment options\">shares and other investment options</a> from the British Private Equity and Venture Capital Association (<abbr title=\"British Private Equity and Venture Capital Association\">BVCA</abbr>).</p>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">business finance and support finder</a> has a list of funding available in the UK.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-explained/loans","slug":"loans","order":2,"title":"Loans","body":"<p>A loan is credit, usually in the form of cash, that you borrow and repay over an agreed length of time. Banks, <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.findingfinance.org.uk/\" title=\"Community Development Finance Institutions\">community development finance institutions,</a> other businesses and even friends and family can provide businesses with loans.</p>\n\n<p>As well as repaying the amount you&rsquo;ve borrowed, you normally have to pay interest on a loan. The amount will depend on:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>how long you need the loan for</li>\n  <li>how much you borrow</li>\n  <li>whether the loan is &lsquo;secured&rsquo; - eg if you own your home and agree to transfer ownership to the loan provider if you don&rsquo;t keep up your payments</li>\n  <li>other factors, like the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/boeapps/iadb/Repo.asp\" title=\"Bank of England base rate\">Bank of England base rate</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The interest rate may be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>fixed, so it won&rsquo;t change for the length of the loan</li>\n  <li>variable, so it will change with the Bank of England base rate or the bank&rsquo;s cost of borrowing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Reasons for getting a loan</h2>\n\n<p>Loans are generally suitable for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>paying for assets - eg vehicles or computers</li>\n  <li>start-up capital</li>\n  <li>instances where the amount of money you need won’t change</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>It’s not a good idea to take out a loan for ongoing expenses – you might find it difficult to keep up repayments.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\n\n<p>Advantages of loans include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>unlike <a href=\"/business-finance-explained/overdrafts\" title=\"Overdrafts\">overdrafts</a>, loans are not repayable on demand - this means that you’re guaranteed the money for the whole term (generally 3 to 10 years)</li>\n  <li>loans can be tied to the lifetime of equipment or other assets you’re borrowing the money to pay for</li>\n  <li>you won’t have to give the lender a percentage of your profits or a share in your company</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\n\n<p>Some disadvantages are that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>loans aren’t very flexible - eg you may have to pay charges if you repay early</li>\n  <li>you might struggle to meet monthly payments if your customers don’t pay you</li>\n  <li>if your loan is secured against your personal property or assets (eg your home) you could lose them if you don&rsquo;t keep up the payments</li>\n  <li>the cost of repayments for variable rate loans can change, making it harder to plan your finances</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>You can look for either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://businessfinanceforyou.co.uk/\" title=\"Business Finance For You\">private finance providers</a> (eg banks)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">public funding</a> (eg government schemes)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-explained/grants","slug":"grants","order":3,"title":"Grants","body":"<p>You can apply for a grant from the government, the European Union, local councils and charities.</p>\n\n<p>You won&rsquo;t need to pay a grant back, but there&rsquo;s a lot of competition and they are almost always awarded for a specific purpose or project.</p>\n\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\n\n<p>Advantages of a grant include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you won&rsquo;t have to pay a grant back or pay interest on it</li>\n  <li>you won&rsquo;t lose any control over your business</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\n\n<p>Some disadvantages are that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you’ll have to find a grant that suits your specific project, which can be difficult</li>\n  <li>there&rsquo;s a lot of competition for grants</li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;ll usually be expected to match the funds you&rsquo;re awarded, eg a grant might cover part of the cost of a project but you&rsquo;ll have to fund some of it yourself</li>\n  <li>grants are usually awarded for proposed projects, not ones that have already started </li>\n  <li>the application process can be time-consuming</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">business finance and support finder</a> has a list of funding available in the UK.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-explained/overdrafts","slug":"overdrafts","order":4,"title":"Overdrafts","body":"<p>An overdraft is a credit facility you agree with your bank. It allows you to temporarily spend more than you have in your account to cover short-term financing needs. </p>\n\n<p>It should not be used as a long-term source of finance - if an overdraft is used persistently your bank may question whether you are in financial difficulty.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to agree your overdraft limit with your bank. You&rsquo;ll usually be charged interest on any money you use, and may also have to pay a fee.</p>\n\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\n\n<p>Advantages of an overdraft include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>it’s flexible - you only borrow what you need at the time, making it cheaper than a <a href=\"/business-finance-explained/loans\" title=\"Loans\">loan</a></li>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s quick to arrange</li>\n  <li>you normally won&rsquo;t be charged for paying off your overdraft earlier than expected</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\n\n<p>Some disadvantages are that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>there will usually be a charge if you want to extend your overdraft</li>\n  <li>you could be charged if you go over your overdraft limit</li>\n  <li>the bank can ask for the money back at any time</li>\n  <li>you can only get an overdraft from the bank that you hold your business current account with</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>You can look for either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://businessfinanceforyou.co.uk/\" title=\"Business Finance For You\">private finance providers</a> (eg banks)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">public funding</a> (eg government schemes)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-explained/invoice-financing","slug":"invoice-financing","order":5,"title":"Invoice financing","body":"<p>Invoice financing is where a third party agrees to buy your unpaid invoices for a fee. Invoice financiers can be independent, or part of a bank or financial institution.</p>\n\n<p>There are two types of invoice financing in the UK.</p>\n\n<h2>Factoring</h2>\n\n<p>&lsquo;Factoring&rsquo; usually involves an invoice financier managing your sales ledger and collecting money owed by your customers themselves. This means your customers will know you&rsquo;re using invoice finance.</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>When you raise an invoice, the invoice financier will buy the debt owed to you by your customer.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>They make a percentage of the cost (usually around 85%) available to you upfront.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>They then collect the full amount directly from your customer.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Once they’ve received the money from your customer, they make the remaining balance available to you.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>You’ll have to them pay a discount charge (interest) and fees - the amount depends on which invoice financier you use.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nYou&rsquo;re owed £40,000 by a customer. You sell the invoice to an invoice financier for £34,000 (85%). They collect £40,000 from your customer and pay you the remaining £6,000 when they receive the money. You pay them interest and any fees you owe.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Invoice discounting</h2>\n\n<p>With &lsquo;invoice discounting&rsquo;, the invoice financier won&rsquo;t manage your sales ledger or collect debts on your behalf. Instead, they lend you money against your unpaid invoices - this is usually an agreed percentage of their total value. You&rsquo;ll have to pay them a fee.</p>\n\n<p>As your customers pay their invoices, the money goes to the invoice financier. This reduces the amount you owe, which means you can then borrow more money on invoices from new sales up to the percentage you originally agreed.</p>\n\n<p>If you use invoice discounting you&rsquo;ll still be responsible for collecting debts, but it can be arranged confidentially so your customers won&rsquo;t find out.</p>\n\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\n\n<p>Both kinds of invoice financing can provide a large and quick boost to your cash flow.</p>\n\n<p>Specific advantages of factoring include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the invoice financier will look after your sales ledger, freeing up your time to manage your business</li>\n  <li>they can help you to negotiate better terms with your suppliers</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Specific advantages of invoice discounting include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>it can be arranged confidentially, so your customers won&rsquo;t know that you&rsquo;re borrowing against their invoices</li>\n  <li>it lets you maintain closer relationships with your customers, because you&rsquo;re still managing their accounts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\n\n<p>Some disadvantages of invoice financing are that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you’ll lose profit from orders or services that you provide</li>\n  <li>invoice financiers will usually only buy commercial invoices - if you sell to the public you might not be eligible </li>\n  <li>it may affect your ability to get other funding, as you won’t have &lsquo;book debts&rsquo; available as security</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you use factoring:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your customers may prefer to deal with you directly</li>\n  <li>it may affect what your customers think of you if the invoice financier deals with them badly</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>You can look for either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://businessfinanceforyou.co.uk/\" title=\"Business Finance For You\">private finance providers</a> (eg banks)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">public funding</a> (eg government schemes)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-explained/leasing-and-asset-finance","slug":"leasing-and-asset-finance","order":6,"title":"Leasing and asset finance","body":"<p>Leasing or renting assets (eg machinery or office equipment) can save you the initial costs of buying them outright.</p>\n\n<h2>Advantages</h2>\n\n<p>Advantages include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you’ll have access to a high standard of equipment that you might not have been able to afford otherwise</li>\n  <li>interest rates on monthly instalments are usually fixed</li>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s a less risky alternative to a secured bank loan - if you can&rsquo;t make payments you&rsquo;ll lose the asset but not, for example, your home</li>\n  <li>as long as you make regular repayments for the period of the lease, the agreement can&rsquo;t be cancelled</li>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s widely available</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Disadvantages</h2>\n\n<p>Disadvantages include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you can&rsquo;t claim <a href=\"/capital-allowances\" title=\"Capital allowances\">capital allowances</a> on a leased asset if the lease period is less than 5 years (or 7 years in some cases)</li>\n  <li>it can be more expensive than buying the asset outright</li>\n  <li>some long-term contracts can be difficult to cancel early</li>\n  <li>you may have to pay a deposit or make some payments in advance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Find funding</h2>\n\n<p>You can look for either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://businessfinanceforyou.co.uk/\" title=\"Business Finance For You\">private finance providers</a> (eg banks)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/business-finance-support-finder\" title=\"business finance and support finder\">public funding</a> (eg government schemes)</li>\n</ul>\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-10-30T14:38:25+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Funding and debt","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Ffunding-debt.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes bankruptcy, business finance and recovering debt","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Ffunding-debt","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/funding-debt"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Setting up","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Fsetting-up.json","web_url":null,"deta